#: src/concepts/channels.md:1
msgid "Channels"
msgstr ""

#: src/concepts/channels.md:3
msgid ""
"Rust is released to three different \"channels\": stable, beta, and nightly. "
"The stable releases are made every 6 weeks (with occasional point releases). "
"Beta releases are the version that will appear in the next stable release. "
"Nightly releases are made every night. See [The Rust Book](https://doc.rust-"
"lang.org/book/appendix-07-nightly-rust.html) for more details on Rust's "
"train release model. The release schedule is posted to the [Rust Forge]"
"(https://forge.rust-lang.org/). `rustup` assists with installing different "
"channels, keeping them up-to-date, and easily switching between them."
msgstr ""

#: src/concepts/channels.md:11
msgid ""
"After a release channel has been installed, `rustup` can be used to update "
"the installed version to the latest release on that channel. See the "
"[Keeping rust up to date](../basics.md#keeping-rust-up-to-date) section for "
"more information."
msgstr ""

#: src/concepts/channels.md:15
msgid ""
"`rustup` can also install specific versions of Rust, such as `1.45.2` or "
"`nightly-2020-07-27`. See the [Toolchains](toolchains.md) chapter for more "
"information on installing different channels and releases. See the "
"[Overrides](../overrides.md) chapter for details on switching between "
"toolchains and pinning your project to a specific toolchain."
msgstr ""

#: src/concepts/channels.md:26
msgid "Working with nightly Rust"
msgstr ""

#: src/concepts/channels.md:28
msgid ""
"`rustup` gives you easy access to the nightly compiler and its [experimental "
"features](https://doc.rust-lang.org/unstable-book/). To add it just run "
"`rustup toolchain install nightly`:"
msgstr ""

#: src/concepts/channels.md:50
msgid ""
"Now Rust nightly is installed, but not activated. To test it out you can run "
"a command from the nightly toolchain like"
msgstr ""

#: src/concepts/channels.md:58
msgid ""
"But more likely you want to use it for a while. To switch to nightly "
"globally, change [the default](../overrides.md#default-toolchain) with "
"`rustup default nightly`:"
msgstr ""

#: src/concepts/channels.md:70
msgid ""
"Now any time you run `cargo` or `rustc` you will be running the nightly "
"compiler."
msgstr ""

#: src/concepts/channels.md:73
msgid ""
"With nightly installed any time you run `rustup update`, the nightly channel "
"will be updated in addition to stable:"
msgstr ""

#: src/concepts/channels.md:90
msgid "Nightly availability"
msgstr ""

#: src/concepts/channels.md:92
msgid ""
"Nightly toolchains may fail to build, so for any given date and target "
"platform there may not be a toolchain available. Furthermore, nightly builds "
"may be published with missing non-default [components](components.md) (such "
"as [`clippy`](https://github.com/rust-lang/rust-clippy)). As such, it can be "
"difficult to find fully-working nightlies. Use the [rustup-components-"
"history](https://rust-lang.github.io/rustup-components-history/) project to "
"find the build status of recent nightly toolchains and components."
msgstr ""

#: src/concepts/channels.md:99
msgid ""
"When you attempt to install or update the `nightly` channel, `rustup` will "
"check if a required or previously installed component is missing. If it is "
"missing, `rustup` will automatically search for an older release that "
"contains the required components. There are several ways to change this "
"behavior:"
msgstr ""

#: src/concepts/channels.md:104
msgid ""
"Use the `--force` flag to `rustup toolchain install` to force it to install "
"the most recent version even if there is a missing component."
msgstr ""

#: src/concepts/channels.md:106
msgid ""
"Use the `--profile` flag to `rustup toolchain install` to use a different "
"profile that does not contain the missing component. For example, `--"
"profile=minimal` should always work, as the minimal set is required to "
"exist. See the [Profiles](profiles.md) chapter for more detail."
msgstr ""

#: src/concepts/channels.md:110
msgid ""
"Install a specific date that contains the components you need. For example, "
"`rustup toolchain install nightly-2020-07-27`. You can then use [overrides]"
"(../overrides.md) to pin to that specific release."
msgstr ""
